<DOC><DOCNO> AP890615-0182 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1950EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-15 0668</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0682</SECOND><HEAD>Severe Storms Over The Southern Atlantic Coast States</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Unseasonably cool air dropped temperatures to record lowsThursday from Minnesota to Texas, and strong thunderstorms developedalong the East Coast.   Thunderstorms developed in warm, humid, unstable air ahead of acold front from western Virginia across western sections of theCarolinas and Georgia into northwestern Florida.   Wind in thunderstorms gusted to 80 mph in Greenville County, S.C.Trees and power lines were blown down near Seneca, S.C., and inGreenville County, the National Weather Service said. Trees alsowere toppled near Polkville, N.C.; Cherokee County, S.C.; nearBostwick, Ga.; near Oglethorpe, Ga., and in Oconee County, Ga., theweather service said.   Rainfall from the storms was also locally heavy. Atlanta receivedthree-quarters of an inch of rain in less than an hour.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included2.82 inches at Troy, Ala.; 2.622 inches at Montgomery, Ala.; 1.14inches at Milton, Fla.; and 1.05 inches at Atlanta.   More than 76,000 residents of the Washington area remainedwithout power Thursday afternoon, down from a peak of 150,000, aftera violent late spring thunderstorm downed electric lines. PotomacElectric Co. officials said Wednesday's storm was the worst, both interms of the numbers of customers affected, and damage to itsequipment, in its 93-year history.   Two days of severe thunderstorms in Alabama were blamed for ahouse fire caused by lightning Thursday and two deaths, plusscattered power outages and damage from Tuscaloosa to Huntsville.   The sky cleared Thursday over much of Texas, after several daysof thunderstorms that brought relief to parched southern Texas, butcaused flooding in northern sections of the state that killed atleast five people, inundated homes and forced evacuations.   From Wednesday until Thursday afternoon, 1 to 1{ inches of rainfell across the upper Ohio Valley and the central Appalachians andrain continued into Thursday night. Greenville, Pa., received 2.3inches of rain in a 24-hour period.   Rain also fell near a cold front extending from northwesternMontana through central Idaho to the northern Pacific Coast.   Unseasonably cool air covered much of the Plains and MississippiValley during the morning, pulled down from the north by thecirculation of a large dome of high pressure centered over westernKansas. Overnight lows dipped to the 30s and 40s from the centralRockies across the northern and central Plains and the upperMississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes.   Nearly 20 cities tied or broke low temperature records:   Amarillo, Texas, 48, a tie; Dodge City, Kan., 44; Duluth, Minn.,35, tie; Eau Claire, Wis., 36; Goodland, Kan., 41; Grand Island,Neb., 40; Huron, S.D., 38; Lincoln, Neb., 44, tie; Midland, Texas,56, tie; Minneapolis, 41; North Platte, Neb., 34; Rochester, Minn.,35, tie; St. Cloud, Minn., 34; Sioux City, Iowa, 41; Sioux Falls,S.D., 37, tie; Spencer, Iowa, 37; Valentine, Neb., 33; Waco, Texas,59, tie; and Wichita, Kan., 54, tie.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 50degrees at Worcester, Mass., to 107 at Needles, Calif. Thursday'slow in the 48 contiguous states was 31 at Shell Lake, Wis.   For Friday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastfrom much of the Atlantic Coast and Florida across the Tennessee andOhio valleys to eastern sections of the upper Great Lakes. Scatteredshowers and some thunderstorms were forecast from the northern highPlains across the northern Rockies into Washington state.   Highs in the 60s were predicted over the upper Great Lakes,northern Maine, and from the central Rockies to the coast ofWashington state; in the 90s over the Florida Peninsula and alongthe southern Atlantic Coast, and from southern and western Texasacross the southern and central Rockies and into interior valleys ofCalifornia; above 100 over the desert Southwest, interior southernCalifornia and near the Big Bend of the Rio Grande in Texas; and inthe 70s and 80s over most of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>